# Security Review: `app.js`

I've completed a thorough review of `/tmp/p15-test-SJFntV/app.js` (23 lines). Here's my analysis:

## Summary

This is a minimal Express.js application with two endpoints (`/health`, `/users`). The current attack surface is small, so the codebase has **no active critical vulnerabilities**, but it is missing nearly all of the defense-in-depth controls you'd want in production. Several issues are latent (they'd become exploitable the moment the app grows) and others are already present.

---

## Findings

### 1. Missing security headers — **Medium** (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)

No `helmet` middleware, so responses lack `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Frame-Options`, CSP, etc.

**Fix:**
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. No rate limiting — **Medium** (OWASP A04: Insecure Design)

Both endpoints are fully open to unbounded request volume (brute force / DoS / enumeration).

**Fix:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 }));
```

### 3. No authentication / authorization on `/users` — **High** (OWASP A01: Broken Access Control, A07: Identification & Auth Failures)

`/users` returns PII (email addresses) with **no auth check**. Anyone on the network can scrape it.

**Fix:** Gate the route behind auth middleware and only return fields the caller is authorized to see:
```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !verifyJwt(token)) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  req.user = decodeJwt(token);
  next();
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return emails to admins
  const users = [
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob',   email: 'bob@example.com' },
  ];
  const safe = req.user.role === 'admin'
    ? users
    : users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name }));
  res.json(safe);
});
```

### 4. CORS not configured — **Medium** (OWASP A05)

With no explicit CORS, Express defaults apply (no `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header — but once someone adds `cors()` carelessly, `*` often sneaks in). Set an explicit allowlist before you need it.

**Fix:**
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'], credentials: true }));
```

### 5. No body-size limits / `express.json()` not bounded — **Low-Medium** (OWASP A04)

Not yet exploitable because no body parser is registered, but the moment one is added it should cap payload size to avoid memory DoS:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '100kb' }));
```

### 6. No input validation framework — **Low today, High later** (OWASP A03: Injection)

No routes currently accept user input, but there is no validator (e.g. `zod`, `joi`, `express-validator`) wired in, so the next PR that adds `req.query`/`req.body`/`req.params` handling will likely ship without validation. Establish the pattern now:

```js
